documents AH service method
comment:
Relation between an Interface Design Description document (of a specific service) and a method of this service.
The relation expresses that the IDD document documents the methods of the service the IDD belongs to.
With this, a consistency check would be possible:
IF a service S has a method M AND the IDD IDD_S is part of the service documentation of S (i.e. IDD_S is the IDD of S)
THEN IDD_S should contain a documentation of M.

label: produces
comment:
Relation expressing that a software system produces a service.
Equivalent names for this relation include: offers, provides, isServiceProducerOf
Since Arrowhead uses the pair produce / consume and corresponding service producer / service consumer adressing the relations and the software systems, this ontology uses these names for the relations too.
If it is needed, object properties with other names can be added and stated to be equivalent to these ones.

label: refers to
comment:
describes the relation between two documentation documents that one document refers to another document.
To our best knowledge, the following relations hold between different types of documentation documents:
- an IDD refers to exactly one SD.
- an SD is referred to by one or more IDD (each stating a way of implementing the service with a specific technolopgy (Source: Arrowhead Framework Definitions V2.4))
- an IDD refers to at most one CP (if it not refers to a CP, then the IDD contains all CP information by itself)
- an IDD refers to n SP, 0 <= n (if it not refers to a SP, then the IDD contains all SP information by itself)
- a SySD refers to one or more IDDs (that is, a system produces one or more services).
- a SySDD refers to one or more SySD's. (Remark HB: I don't understand this. How can one concrete white box description of a system fulfill (support / implement) different black box descriptions of systems? The other way around seems to be possible as between SDs and IDDs).
- an SoSD refers to n SySD's.
- an SoSDD refers to n SoSD's.
- an SoSDD refers to n SySD's.
- an SoSDD refers to n SySDDs.

label: refers to CP
comment:
an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Communication Profile (CP).
No other documentation document can refer to a CP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs.
An IDD can refer to a CP, but this is not mandatory. CPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same CP. Then the CP information should be extracted to an CP document and the IDDs of all services that use this CP shall refer to this CP.
If the CP is unique for a specific service, the CP information can directly be included in the IDD.
If the IDD refers to a CP, this must be a unique reference. That is, one IDD must not refer to different CPs. Hence this object property is functional. (If the service could be implemented using different communication technologies, each implementation would need an own IDD!!).

label: refers to SP
comment:
an Interface Design Description (IDD) can refer to a Semantic Profile (SP).
No other documentation document can refer to a SP. Hence the domain of this object property is the class of IDDs.
An IDD can refer to a SP, but this is not mandatory. SPs are intended to be used in cases in which several services use the same SP. Then the SCP information should be extracted to an SP document and the IDDs of all services that use this SP shall refer to this SP.
If the SP is unique for a specific service, the SP information can directly be included in the IDD.
References to SPs are not necessarily unique for an IDD. That is, different methods of the service documented by the IDD can use different Semantic Profiles.
